Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Prosecuting attorney Jeanette Kara Corbett in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant appears via video in custody from the Washington County Jail and by Attorney Timothy Drewa via video. Defendant given complaint, advised of charges, penalties and rights, and probable cause found.  Court has colloquy with Defendant regarding right to be physically present at today's hearing and accepts consent to use of video conferencing.  Defendant not eligible for State Public Defender.  Not guilty plea entered by Court.  Court appoints Atty. Gordon Leech.  Defendant shall reimburse Washington County at a rate of $50 per month commencing 10-01-2022.  State requests $1,000 cash bond.  Court sets $1,000 cash bond.  Adjourned to allow defendant to appear with Atty. Leech.  Hearing scheduled for September 21, 2022 at 08:15 am.
